 {"id":"bd-320","title":"Integrate rich logging into FastMCP server startup","description":"## Purpose and Rationale

Wire the RichTracingSubscriber into FastMCP's server startup path so that all logging throughout the server lifecycle displays with rich formatting. This is the integration point that makes all the logging work visible.

## Background

FastMCP servers are typically started via Server::run_stdio(). This is the ideal location to initialize the rich tracing subscriber because:
1. It happens early enough to capture all logs
2. We have access to configuration
3. We can detect the display context (agent vs human)

## Technical Specification

### Integration Point

```rust
// crates/fastmcp/src/server.rs

impl Server {
    pub async fn run_stdio(self) -> Result<(), Error> {
        // NEW: Initialize rich logging early
        self.init_rich_logging()?;

        // Existing startup banner (from Phase 2)
        self.display_startup_banner();

        // Rest of existing implementation...
        let (stdin, stdout) = (io::stdin(), io::stdout());
        // ...
    }

    fn init_rich_logging(&self) -> Result<(), Error> {
        use fastmcp_console::logging::RichSubscriberBuilder;

        // Get configuration from server config or environment
        let log_level = self.config.log_level.unwrap_or(LevelFilter::INFO);
        let show_timestamps = self.config.log_timestamps.unwrap_or(true);

        // Build and initialize subscriber
        RichSubscriberBuilder::new()
            .with_level_filter(log_level)
            .with_timestamps(show_timestamps)
            .with_theme(self.console_theme.clone())
            .init()
            .map_err(|e| Error::Internal(format\!("Failed to init logging: {}", e)))?;

        tracing::debug\!("Rich logging initialized");
        Ok(())
    }
}
```

