### Environment Variable Support

Honor standard logging environment variables:

```rust
impl LoggingConfig {
    pub fn from_env() -> Self {
        Self {
            level: std::env::var("FASTMCP_LOG")
                .ok()
                .and_then(|s| s.parse().ok()),
            timestamps: std::env::var("FASTMCP_LOG_TIMESTAMPS")
                .map(|s| s \!= "0" && s.to_lowercase() \!= "false")
                .unwrap_or(true),
            // ... etc
        }
    }
}
```

### Fallback Behavior

If rich logging init fails, fall back to standard tracing:

```rust
fn init_rich_logging(&self) -> Result<(), Error> {
    match RichSubscriberBuilder::new()
        .with_level_filter(log_level)
        .init() 
    {
        Ok(()) => Ok(()),
        Err(e) => {
            // Fall back to standard fmt subscriber
            eprintln\!("Warning: Rich logging unavailable: {}", e);
            tracing_subscriber::fmt()
                .with_max_level(log_level)
                .with_writer(std::io::stderr)
                .init();
            Ok(())
        }
    }
}
```

## Implementation Steps

1. Add LoggingConfig to ServerConfig struct
2. Implement from_env() for environment variable parsing
3. Add init_rich_logging() method to Server
4. Call init_rich_logging() early in run_stdio()
5. Add fallback to standard tracing on failure
6. Update Server builder to accept logging config
7. Add integration tests

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Rich logging initializes before any log output
- [ ] Configuration is respected (level, timestamps, etc)
- [ ] Environment variables override defaults
- [ ] Fallback works if rich logging fails
- [ ] No interference with JSON-RPC on stdout
- [ ] All server logs display with rich formatting
- [ ] Integration tests verify log output

